fyi new dx cmd
```[8:14:38] ~/dev/sm/code/dx [master u=](sm.dev)(aws:dev)> dx aws sign-token --help
dx aws sign-token

Signs a token for you to call an api.

The most straight forward tokens are ones that doesn't have any custom claims.
To sign those the command just needs to know the follow about the api you want to call
* environment
* system
* component

With that it will figure out where the following info based on most common convention
* secret (<s3://sm.secrets.dev/<env>/<system>/<component>/jwt_secret>)
* audience (<system>/component)

e.g.
dx aws sign-token --system tbb --environment nxs-dev --component core-api-apac

But if the api you want to call uses custom claims then you can give this command some additional info to figure out the payload to use.

One of the easiest way is to copy the claims from an existing token.
Now you might be wondering if you have an existing token then why bother going through this?
Well... the answer is that in the near future there will no longer be permenant tokens.

So if give the command info about another app that calls the api you want to call and the command will use the same claims when signing you a token.

e.g.
dx aws sign-token --system tbb --environment nxs-dev --component core-api-apac --claimsEnvironment nxs-dev --claimsSystem nxs-tbb --claimsComponent nxs-events

p.s. if any of those conventions does not match, then you are SOL'ed.

p.s.s this only works against the dev realm.

since github changed their UI, creating PR from (what i can tell) the default branch (usually develop) to master is a pita so i finally created an alias for it
```gpr () {
	if [ -z "$1" ]
	then
		echo "Error: specify target branch"
		return 0
	fi
	repo=$(git remote -v | grep fetch | grep origin | sed -e's/.*github.com.//' | sed -e's/\.git.*//') 
	current_branch=$(git branch --show-current) 
	open "<https://github.com/${repo}/compare/${1}...${current_branch}>"
}```

• What type of instagram account is this? (2c each)
